			<parts.title>Cocaygne. Interpretation: 1) Gula and Desidia or/and; 2) They don't try to get the good they want: 2 sleep - clerk is waiting for the good to come, knight looks longingly to the good - but if they don't do anything themselves they won't get anything in the land of Cocaygne: with other words : praise of work.</parts.title>
			<parts.title>[recto] Cocaygne. Gula. Bax, Ontcijfering, citaat p. 178; [toegevoegde vermelding]: 'F.G. Also in 'Cuis ? Grasse (B. 159) there are pig frotters and almost all food is pork or made from pork (hams, sausages) and there is a goose on the table like in Cocaygne. The pig is the animal of Gula!; [verso] [...][scan]</parts.title>
			<parts.title>Vices & Avarice, Gula (Greed) Avaritia ist das erste der Laster das Bruegel zeichnete, 1556, alle anderen 1557!</parts.title>
			<parts.title>Alchemist. Alchemie ist Gier nach Gold, Besitz, nach irdischen Gut. Narrenschiff, citaat  I, 102 [= vo falsch und beschiss] Abgeschnitt: Do mit ich nit vergeß hie by [...]  Gar wenig sint syn worden rich.</parts.title>
			<parts.title>Hans Sebald Beham, Titelblatt (Holzschnitt) zu Hans Sachsens [Ain] Dialogus und Argument der Romanisten wider das Christlich heliflein, den Geytz und ander offentlich Laster betreffend (Ephesians 5 [...] (1524) ([Heinrich]Röttinger, Ergänzungen und Berichtigungen des Sebald Beham-Kataloges Gustav Paulis, Straatsburg, 1927, N° 1197a (Taf. 5); Abb. auch R. Zoozmann, Hans Sachs und die Reformation, [Dresden: Angermann, 1904] p. 105, und [Karl] Kaulfuss-Diesch, Das Buch der Reformation, [Leipzig] 2. Aufl., p. 313.</parts.title>
			<parts.title>[recto] Ad [Addendum] Alchemist Warb.Inst. "Alchemy" 1) Frinks (?) pinxit Abrahamus Jacobus sculpsit, [monogram van Cornelis Visscher excudit with 4 lines in Dutch & French Onmogelijck Wie heeft oijt sien wonder rijck [...] Shows woman sitting with book and versions alchemist & instruments behind her a negro (devil ? and in background man working on fire; [verso] Pieter van der Borcht: Monkeys as Alchemists - all figures monkeys, but otherwise very similar to Bruegel and in background view of the poor monkey alchemist family arriving at a house where they are welcomed. There is clearly a connection between to this print. Ex. C. Veth, Geschiedenis van de Nederlandsche Caricaturen, Leiden, 1921, p. 113.</parts.title>
			<parts.title>Avaritia. Toad of Avaritia exactly in centre at bottom.</parts.title>
			<parts.title>Music & Luxuria. Bax, p. 155: Speellieden zetten aan tot onkuisheid [...]</parts.title>
			<parts.title>Bruegel: Inhalt - Gegenstand. Dvorák, Gesch. der ital. Kst, 1928, II, citaat p.122.</parts.title>
			<parts.title>[recto] Ad [Addendum] Romdahl: Youth preshed into pigsty & greed (gula); Hausenstein, Bauern-Bruegel, 1910, citaat p. 58 Magere und Fette Küche [...]; [verso] p. 58 Das Luilekkerland ist Apotheose des Schlemmerei; [toegevoegde vermelding] 'F.G. Gula motivs & contrasts: 1) Gula 1557/58; 2) Carnival & Lent 1559; 3) Küchscène Magere & Grosse 1563; 4) Land of Cocaygne 1567; 5) Youth pushed into Pigsty (Bast. 164) 1568; 6) Copenhagen: 2 Fat Heads and one lean one) z.T. gehören hierbei auch Kirmes, Stiche und Bilder.</parts.title>
			<parts.title>Bruegel & Rabelais. Hausenstein, Der Bauern-Bruegel, 1910, citaten pp. 124-125.</parts.title>
			<parts.title>Cornelis Veth, Geschiedenis van de Nederlandsche caricaturen, Leiden, 1921, citaten pp. 97-98.</parts.title>
